import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { nextGeneration } from "./game-of-life.js";

describe("Game of Life", () => {
  it("should return empty grid when given empty grid", () => {
    const result = nextGeneration([]);
    expect(result).toEqual([]);
  });
  it("should kill a single cell with no neighbors (underpopulation)", () => {
    const result = nextGeneration([[0, 0]]);
    expect(result).toEqual([]);
  });
  it("should kill cells with only one neighbor (underpopulation)", () => {
    const result = nextGeneration([[0, 1], [1, 1]]);
    expect(result).toEqual([]);
  });
  it("should bring a dead cell to life when it has exactly 3 live neighbors (reproduction)", () => {
    const result = nextGeneration([[0, 0], [1, 0], [0, 1]]);
    expect(result).toEqual([[1, 1]]);
  });
  it.todo("should keep a live cell alive when it has 2 or 3 neighbors (survival)");
  it.todo("should kill a live cell with more than 3 neighbors (overpopulation)");
  it.todo("should keep a block pattern unchanged (still life)");
  it.todo("should oscillate a blinker pattern (oscillator)");
});
```

Use the spec example for survival: three cells in a row [(0,1), (1,1), (2,1)], where center cell (1,1) has 2 neighbors and survives. Also reproduction creates new cells. The expected result should include (1,1) surviving plus any reproduced cells. Let me think through the full expected output:

Input: [(0,1), (1,1), (2,1)] — horizontal line
- Cell (0,1): has neighbors (1,1) → 1 neighbor → dies
- Cell (1,1): has neighbors (0,1), (2,1) → 2 neighbors → survives
- Cell (2,1): has neighbors (1,1) → 1 neighbor → dies
- Dead cell (1,0): neighbors are (0,1), (1,1), (2,1) → 3 neighbors → born
- Dead cell (1,2): neighbors are (0,1), (1,1), (2,1) → 3 neighbors → born

Expected: [[1,0], [1,1], [1,2]] — vertical line (the blinker!)

This test WILL fail because the current implementation only returns reproduced cells, not surviving ones. It will return [[1,0], [1,2]] but miss [1,1].

